    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "8104defd405b44dd0bef3b510b922d08",
      "text": "As a first-year student at [[Harvard University]] in fall 1970, Stallman was known for his strong performance in Math. He was happy:<blockquote>For the first time in my life, I felt I had found a home at Harvard.<?blockquote>"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fce46b999c546ef0407cfb51ec34ed6a",
      "text": "In 1971, near the end of his first year at Harvard, he became a programmer at the [[MIT Artificial Intelligence Laboratory]], and became a regular in the [[hacker]] community, where he was usually known by his initials, ''RMS'' (which was the name of his computer accounts)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7345e1b0075c08a8",
      "text": "Stallman graduated from Harvard ''magna cum laude'' earning a bachelor's degree in Physics in 1974 - [https://www.stallman.org/biographies.html#serious stallman.org]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5856256a10bb3020b58082de5f895064",
      "text": "Stallman considered staying on at Harvard, but instead he decided to enrol as a graduate student at MIT. He ended his pursuit of a doctorate in physics after one year, in order to focus on his programming at the MIT AI Laboratory."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "6401d534bd2861a97e90e8fa76f1e47f",
      "text": "# Dependency-directed Backtracking"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "acaff93c1b6f1a71",
      "text": "While working (starting in 1975) as a research assistant at MIT under [[Gerald Jay Sussman]], Stallman published a paper (with Sussman) in 1977 on an AI [[truth maintenance system]], called ''dependency-directed backtracking''."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "16e0db579bf3424b",
      "text": "This paper was an early work on the problem of intelligent backtracking in [[constraint satisfaction problem]]s. As of 2009, the technique Stallman and Sussman introduced is still the most general and powerful form of intelligent backtracking."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "86d90a8188e0e6b6",
      "text": " The technique of constraint recording ([[constraint learning]]), wherein partial results of a search are recorded for later reuse, was also introduced in this paper."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c1d9a4b6c6fb8881fae48506546f76f9",
      "text": "# MIT"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1c816c2cbd582f92",
      "text": "As a hacker in MIT's AI laboratory, Stallman worked on software projects such as [[TECO (text editor)]], [[Emacs]] for ITS ([[Incompatible Timesharing System]]), and the [[Lisp Machine]] operating system. This latter unit was commercialised by [[Symbolics]] and LMI ([[Lisp Machines, Inc.]]) starting around 1980)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d37d16ec6c93527c",
      "text": "He would become an ardent critic of restricted computer access in the lab, which at that time was funded primarily by the Defence Advanced Research Projects Agency ([[DARPA]]). "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8800be76275c29d1",
      "text": "When MIT's ([[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]) Laboratory for Computer Science ([[Project MAC]]) (LCS) installed a password control system in 1977, Stallman found a way to decrypt the passwords and sent users messages containing their decoded password, with a suggestion to change it to the empty string (that is, no password) instead, to re-enable anonymous access to the systems. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "792edb7018d59c3a",
      "text": "Around 20% of the users followed his advice at the time, although passwords ultimately prevailed. Stallman boasted of the success of his campaign for many years afterward."
    },
